Role of macrophages in chronic inflammation

  • Sweet tasting. (animal poisoning is common from radiator leaks)
  • Like ethyl alcohol and methanol, ethylene glycol is metabolized by ADH. In this step it forms glycoaldehyde. Through interaction with aldehyde dehydrogenase, ethylene glycol is then metabolized to glycolic acid (GA), which accumulates and can cause a profound metabolic acidosis. This glycolic acid is eventually converted into glyoxylic acid, and then into the highly toxic oxalate or the safer glutamate or -ketoadipic acid metabolites.
    Acanthosis nigricans is associated with many, many cancers.

Erythema gyratum repens : 80% is associated with cancer. Cutaneous manifestaion occurs before the tumour symptoms (upto 6 years before).

[!INFO] Uricase
Gout is rare in most other animals due to their ability to produce uricase, which breaks down uric acid.[115] Humans and other great apes do not have this ability; -Wikipedia

  • Much commoner in men (5:1)
  • 80% of the time, gout is monoarticular.
  • Polycarticular flares usually occurs in chronic gout.
  • Initial presentaion with polyarticular pattern may be due to underlying malignancy
  • trauma, surgery, starvation, exercise
  • Fructose rich foods
  • Joints affected by osteoarthritis are at higher risk of gout.
    Usually acute attacks occur at night.
    Acute flare will peak in about 24 hours and resolve even without treatment by 7 days.
    • Mnemonic: stat - stop oxidase
    • Mnemonic: case uricase / pegloticase

      | Gout | Pseudogout |
      | ---- | ---- |
      | Uric acid crystal | Calcium pyrophosphate |
      | Needle shaped, negatively birefingent | Rhomboid shaped, positively birefringent |
      | Associated with triggers (heavy meal, alcohol, illness, dehydration) | No acute triggers |

      | | also, hyperparathyroidism, hypomagnesemia, haemochromatosis |

      | Uric acid levels fall immediately after an episode | |
      | Commonest joint: MTP, also wrist, ankle | knee, elbow, wrist, ankle |

Langhans cell histiocytosis

Langhans cell histiocytosis
Buerher granules presnt on EM.
More common in children (1-3 years of age) but can present in any age even in adults.
Is one cause of interstitial lung disease.
Adults presents with pulmonary involvement.

Single system LCH ->
Only one system involved.
Adults commonly have single system involvement.

Multisystem LCH -> two or more systems involved.
pituitary involvement -> commonest manifestation if diabetes insipidus.

Adults commonly have lytic lesions in the jaw and skull.
Pulmonary involvement: also commoner in adults. non productive cough, spontaneous pneumothorax, chest pain etc.
Upper and middle zone involvement is characteristic.

Fuller's earth: A type of clay used as an adsorbent, filter or bleaching agent. Used in 'kitty litter' to remove the smell of cat urine.
Medically, used for treatment of paraquat ingestion, because [[Toxicology#Paraquat poisoning|Paraquat]] is intended to break down in soil. Source

Mnemonic: Allergic Turtle Attack

  • Overall low incidence of side effects.
  • Peripheral neuropathy, esp in malnourished / alcoholic/ pregnant
  • Optic neuritis : Towards end of treatment .
  • Hepatitis
  • Histaminase inhibitors -> incrased histamine levels -> erythema, headachage, N/V/D -> patients must avoid red fish.
  • Acetylation is not done by the P450 enzyme system.
  • Pt is rapid acetylator -> increased hepatotoxic biproduct level -> increased risk of hepatitis if isoniazid
  • Pt is slow acetylator -> increased concentration of unmetabolized isoniazid -> increased risk of peripheral neuroathy. (==p==re-metabolism - ==p==eripheral neuropathy)
  • Pyridoxine 10mg oral is coadministered.
